<edge source="concept.ambition" target="concept.honor_recognition" id="edge.concept.ambition.concerns_honor.concept.honor_recognition">
  <data key="d6">edge.concept.ambition.concerns_honor.concept.honor_recognition</data>
  <data key="d7">concept.ambition</data>
  <data key="d8">Ambition</data>
  <data key="d9">vice</data>
  <data key="d10">concerns_honor</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.honor_recognition</data>
  <data key="d12">Honor as Recognition</data>
  <data key="d13">domain</data>
  <data key="d14">ann.concept-ambition-concerns-honor-concept-honor-recognition-st-ii-ii-q131-a001-resp | ann.concept-ambition-concerns-honor-concept-honor-recognition-st-ii-ii-q131-a002-resp</data>
  <data key="d15">st.ii-ii.q131.a001.resp | st.ii-ii.q131.a002.resp</data>
  <data key="d16">explicit_textual</data>
  <data key="d17">an ought so far to be pleased that others bear witness to his excellence, as this enables him to profit others. Now the desire of honor may be inordinate in three ways. First, when a man desires recognition of an excellence which he has not: this is to desire more than his share of honor . Seco | As stated above ( Article 1 ), ambition signifies inordinate love of honor . Now magnanimity is about honors and makes use of them in a becoming manner. Wherefore it is evident that ambition is opposed to magnanimity as the inordinate</data>
  <data key="d18">reviewed_doctrinal</data>
  <data key="d19">honor_worthiness</data>
</edge>
<edge source="concept.ambition" target="concept.honor_recognition" id="edge.concept.ambition.directed_to.concept.honor_recognition">
  <data key="d6">edge.concept.ambition.directed_to.concept.honor_recognition</data>
  <data key="d7">concept.ambition</data>
  <data key="d8">Ambition</data>
  <data key="d9">vice</data>
  <data key="d10">directed_to</data>
  <data key="d11">concept.honor_recognition</data>
  <data key="d12">Honor as Recognition</data>
  <data key="d13">domain</data>
